  "prompt": "Does sound travel through empty space?",
  "response": "No, sound does not travel through empty space. Sound is a mechanical wave that requires a medium, such as air, water, or a solid, to propagate. It travels by causing particles in the medium to vibrate, transferring energy from one particle to the next. \n\nIn empty space, there is no medium\u2014such as air or other particles\u2014to carry these vibrations, so sound cannot travel. This is why space is often described as \"silent.\" If you were in the vacuum of space, you would not hear any sounds, even from nearby events like a supernova or a spaceship explosion.",
